IELTS Band Requirements for Australia

  • 2313 Reads
  • 3 min Read
  • By:CANAM Group
  • Updated On:Apr 08,2023 05:02 PM IST

Just like every other English-speaking country, the Australian education system also requires international students to prove their language proficiency. Here is everything you need to know about IELTS, a popular language test.

Telegram Whatsapp Facebook Linked In Twitter


With the third highest number of international students in the world, Australia is one of the most popular study-abroad destinations. The country is home to 1000+ academic institutes offering over 22,000 courses in fields like natural sciences & mathematics, life & agricultural sciences, clinical medicine & pharmacy, physics, and arts & culinary.

Reasons to study in Australia:

Australia accounts for all the factors that make it a perfect country to study for international students, including diversity of cultures, affordable living costs, quality of life, and ample work opportunities both on-campus and off-campus. The city life and Australia's scenic beauty also attract students worldwide. 

Many Australian vocational courses and degrees include work experience programs and internships, which help students gain hands-on industry experience allowing them to grow professionally and build a network while studying.

Importance of IELTS scores for admission to Australian institutes?

Since English is the native language of Australia, international students who wish to study here are required to prove their English language proficiency through tests like IELTS. Hence, it is an important admission requirement in Australia.

How many bands are required to study in Australia?

There are a number of top-ranked universities and colleges in Australia, each with different admission criteria or IELTS requirements. Generally, to pursue an undergraduate program, a student needs to have a minimum score of 6.0 band overall in IELTS, with no less than 6.0 band in every module. On the other hand, to enrol for a Master's degree, students need to score at least 6.5 bands overall with a minimum of 6.0 bands in every module. 

Tips to get a high score in IELTS:

Since the purpose of IELTS is to measure the student's understanding of the English language, it is important for them to be good in all four skills (reading, writing, speaking, and listening) to secure a seat in their preferred institute. 

In order to score well in IELTS, students need to develop a good understanding of the basics of the English language, such as grammar, vocabulary, different accents, etc. Here are certain tips for scoring well in every module:

Writing Module:

Writing is considered to be the most difficult section, as students are judged on various parameters before giving any band. There are many approaches to this section, but the best way to prepare for it is to practice daily. For Task 1, Search for different types of graphs/tables/diagram descriptions, evaluate them and explain the same in the most concise way possible.

To write an article for task 2, students should focus on framing different sentence structures showcasing the knowledge of a range of vocabulary words. To enhance their essay-writing skills, students should read articles from websites, newspapers, and magazines.

Reading Module:

The preparation of the reading module is no different than writing as to improve reading abilities, students are advised to read English-language journals, newspapers, magazines, and books while highlighting the fewer frequent words. Regular practice of different types of questions can help students quickly understand the demand of the question and pick the right approach to answer it.

Listening Module:

The key to scoring well in this section is to listen to radio, podcasts, or news in different English accents and try to understand the conversation. While listening to different accents, students should pay attention to the pace of speaking and pronunciation. Students should practice different types of sample papers and answer questions accordingly.

Speaking Module:

This module requires a student to converse with the examiner in English and give relevant answers to questions. To get a high band in this section, students should utilize every opportunity to practice speaking with their peers and focus on improving fluency and pronunciation.

Therefore, it is advised to take the help of experts who can fulfill the admission requirements and guide the students in successfully completing all these procedures.

FAQ

What IELTS score is required for a Master's degree from Australia?

To apply for a master’s degree, students must fulfil the minimum score requirement of 6.5 bands, with no band less than 6.0 in each section.

Which exam is better for Australia: IELTS or PTE?

PTE and IELTS are globally accepted language proficiency tests showcasing a candidate's familiarity with the English language. Both these tests are accepted for Australian student visa and migration applications.

What is the minimum passing score for IELTS in Australia?

For an undergraduate program, students need to score a minimum of overall 6 bands, whereas, for postgraduate programs, students need to have an overall score of 6.5 bands with 6.0 bands in each module.

How much time is needed to score well in IELTS?

The amount of time needed for IELTS preparation greatly depends on a candidate's current English proficiency levels. Candidates who are fluent in the language can prepare in less than 2 months, but those with moderate language skills might need 3-4 months to score well on the test.

Can students work during their studies in Australia?

Students are allowed to work 20 hours a week during their academic sessions and full-time during session breaks.

What accommodation options are available for students in Australia?

Students can choose between on-campus or off-campus accommodation options. The majority of Australian universities provide on-campus housing options for international students.

Is it possible to apply for study in Australia without IELTS?

Students can apply for study in Australia without IELTS only if they complete their studies in nations that the Australian Education System acknowledges.
